oal ranged widely, from “ultra” utopians and nascent feminists to black abolitionists. Riotous Flesh explains how and why diverse women came together to popularize, then institutionalize, the condemnation of masturbation, well before the advent of sexology or the professionalization of medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFemale masturbation - Social aspects - United States - History - 19th century. 0aFemale masturbationxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aFeminismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenxSexual behaviorxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxAttitudesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  afeminist theory, feminism, 19th century america, united states, gender, womens studies, illness, insanity, death, health concerns, politics, political, sex, sexuality, sexual behavior, unexpected alliances, medical history, social issues, self-abuse, education, black abolitionists, sexology, female masturbation, licentiousness, amative indulgence, solitary vice.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022628459040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226284767423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226284767/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles